1
00:00:12,120 --> 00:00:15,829
Hello. Allow me to introduce myself.

2
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:18,036
I am Jackie Mulchen,

3
00:00:18,200 --> 00:00:22,591
the executive producer in charge
of all productions here at Paramount.

4
00:00:22,760 --> 00:00:27,311
And before showing this picture,
I thought I should at least explain.

5
00:00:27,480 --> 00:00:31,268
The motion picture you're about to see
isn't the run-of-the-mill film fare

6
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:35,228
that has been presented
to the movie going public of late.

7
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:40,159
It's quite easy
making this type of picture,

8
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:43,517
filled with love, emotion and tears.

9
00:00:44,440 --> 00:00:47,910
And of course, we could easily
make the space...

10
00:00:48,080 --> 00:00:49,479
...violence...

11
00:00:49,640 --> 00:00:53,633
...and horror films that are enjoyed
by many peoples of the world.

12
00:00:55,320 --> 00:00:58,915
But we chose to make
what you're about to see.

13
00:00:59,080 --> 00:01:02,038
A film based on fun.

14
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:07,832
And it's just a little different
insofar as there is no story and no plot.

15
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,437
That's right. I said no story, no plot.

16
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:16,275
It is actually a series of silly sequences.

17
00:01:16,440 --> 00:01:19,352
Or you might say it is a visual diary

18
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:23,832
of a few weeks in the life of a real nut.

19
00:01:26,760 --> 00:01:28,671
And it's real silly.

20
00:01:31,640 --> 00:01:34,518
Oh, put it on. Show it to 'em. Put it on!

21
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:49,876
<i>This is Walter Winchell reporting,</i>

22
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:52,190
<i>and this is Miami Beach at night.</i>

23
00:01:52,360 --> 00:01:55,511
<i>The nights here are the same
as anywhere else.</i>

24
00:01:55,680 --> 00:01:58,399
<i>No sun.</i>

25
00:01:58,560 --> 00:02:01,836
<i>This is the same Miami Beach, daytime.</i>

26
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:06,437
<i>It is just waking up,
rubbing the sand out of its palms,</i>

27
00:02:06,600 --> 00:02:10,479
<i>ready for another "let's be pretty
for the tourists" day,</i>

28
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:12,437
<i>a day that could never get started</i>

29
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,431
<i>without the people who provide
the services</i>

30
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:18,878
<i>that are required in order
that the visitor is satisfied.</i>

31
00:02:19,040 --> 00:02:21,634
<i>The people who serve
are the real backbone,</i>

32
00:02:21,800 --> 00:02:25,475
<i>the people who serve and work
in order that you might pay...</i>

33
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:27,437
<i>... that is, play.</i>

34
00:02:49,240 --> 00:02:51,993
Company... halt!

35
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:56,076
<i>And of course, there are chefs,
chambermaids, clerks, hostesses,</i>

36
00:02:56,240 --> 00:02:58,800
<i>waiters, doormen,
bartenders, waitresses,</i>

37
00:02:58,960 --> 00:03:01,155
<i>musicians and entertainers.</i>

38
00:03:02,520 --> 00:03:05,956
<i>But these men are
the real unsung heroes of a hotel,</i>

39
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:08,873
<i>the men who have no real direction.</i>

40
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:11,395
<i>They are called on day and night,
for anything,</i>

41
00:03:11,560 --> 00:03:14,154
<i>from burping babies
to walking the dog.</i>

42
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:17,676
<i>These are the men who are
almost always called upon</i>

43
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:21,799
<i>for services above and beyond
the call of duty.</i>

44
00:03:21,960 --> 00:03:24,599
<i>Yes, ladies and gentlemen,
I call them men,</i>

45
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:28,230
<i>but everyone else
calls for... the bellboy.</i>

46
00:03:45,920 --> 00:03:51,278
<i>As the bellboys break ranks, they all
know where to go and what to do.</i>

47
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:53,476
<i>That is, most of them.</i>

48
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:47,111
How are you?

49
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:55,317
Here, Stanley. Get everything
out of the trunk.

50
00:06:13,560 --> 00:06:15,357
George, come help me.

51
00:06:15,520 --> 00:06:17,795
Hello? Hello?

52
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:19,678
Hello, Mr Hartman. How are you?

53
00:06:19,840 --> 00:06:22,832
- Yes, we...
- I need a couple of guys...

54
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,560
Yes, we have your trunks.

55
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:29,474
I can't hear very well.
What did you say?

56
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:31,471
Oh, yes, of course.

57
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:35,713
We've got beautiful accommodations.
I'm sure you'll be happy with them.

58
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:38,997
We'd be delighted to see you. Yes.

59
00:06:39,160 --> 00:06:41,390
Yes, thank you. Goodbye.

60
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:24,750
- I'm Mr Carter. I have a reservation.
- Yes, sir, Mr Carter. Sign here, please.

61
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,150
It's nice to have you with us again.

62
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:32,518
Unfortunately, I can't stay too long.
This has to be a hit-and-run vacation.

63
00:07:32,680 --> 00:07:36,468
We certainly hope you enjoy your stay.
Front boy!

64
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:39,677
Mr Carter is in Room 625.

65
00:07:41,280 --> 00:07:44,590
We certainly hope you enjoy your stay,
Miss Winkly.

66
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:46,352
Front boy!

67
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:50,118
Miss Winkly is in Room 626.

68
00:07:52,480 --> 00:07:56,189
It's so nice to see you again,
Mrs Hartong. Let me help you.

69
00:08:02,960 --> 00:08:06,748
You're very lucky. We've been having
wonderful weather, Mrs Hartong.

70
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:10,071
Here we go, that's it. Easy.

71
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:12,117
That's it now.

72
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:39,076
Boy, open that bag
and hang those things up in the closet.

73
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:14,431
Well, if it isn't Mrs Hartong
back with us again.

74
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:17,797
I hope it isn't because of dieting again.

75
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:21,916
Don't you fret. We'll do all we can.

76
00:09:22,080 --> 00:09:24,674
But you'll have to stay away
from the candy.

77
00:09:24,840 --> 00:09:26,637
- I know, I know.
- Good.

78
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:30,509
Clerk, the key to Room 988
for Mrs Hartong, please.

79
00:09:30,680 --> 00:09:34,434
I'm sure you'll be very happy
in the new wing, Mrs Hartong.

80
00:09:45,720 --> 00:09:47,836
I'd like to leave a forwarding address.

81
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:49,399
Certainly.

82
00:09:51,920 --> 00:09:54,275
Two weeks certainly did fly by,
Mrs Hartong.

83
00:09:54,440 --> 00:09:56,032
They certainly did.

84
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:58,794
- You look wonderful.
- Thank you.

85
00:09:58,960 --> 00:10:00,791
You kept away from the candy.

86
00:10:00,960 --> 00:10:03,713
- Goodbye, Mr Novak. Thank you.
- Goodbye.

87
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:08,113
Move that car over.
Pull it over, that's it.

88
00:10:08,280 --> 00:10:12,717
Now move the other one!
What a day I've put in.

89
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:15,599
Oh, Mrs Hartong,
I didn't recognise you.

90
00:10:15,760 --> 00:10:18,957
You look crazy. I mean, great.

91
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:22,157
Thank you, Carl.
Has my uncle's car arrived yet?

92
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:24,595
Not yet, Mrs Hartong.
I'll call and check.

93
00:10:24,760 --> 00:10:26,159
Thank you.

94
00:10:28,400 --> 00:10:29,913
Mrs Hartong is right here.

95
00:10:30,080 --> 00:10:33,789
Mrs Hartong, your uncle asked
if you would please wait.

96
00:10:33,960 --> 00:10:36,155
He'll be here in 20 minutes.

97
00:10:36,320 --> 00:10:38,880
- That'll be fine. I'll wait.
- All right.

98
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:41,918
Mrs Hartong said it'll be fine. Thank you.

99
00:10:42,920 --> 00:10:46,071
- Would you care to sit here?
- Thank you.

100
00:11:27,200 --> 00:11:31,193
Stanley, you've been at this
for 40 minutes. Get going, will you?

101
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:38,668
I don't mind you helping the guys.
But you've been here for over an hour.

102
00:11:38,840 --> 00:11:42,071
Get back to the bell desk.
On the double!

103
00:11:45,640 --> 00:11:47,073
Stanley!

104
00:12:09,960 --> 00:12:11,916
- I don't get it.
- Get what?

105
00:12:12,080 --> 00:12:13,798
This kid loves his work.

106
00:12:16,160 --> 00:12:20,358
Now you've got that done, please be
good enough... Let me rephrase that.

107
00:12:20,520 --> 00:12:26,152
To keep you out of mischief, set up
the seats for the motion picture tonight.

108
00:12:26,320 --> 00:12:30,199
Stanley, we don't talk back.
Get along, get along.

109
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:52,318
What is it?
I've never seen you laugh so hard.

110
00:13:52,480 --> 00:13:54,675
I've got Stanley
on theatre seating duty.

111
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:57,035
Alone?
How long has he been in there?

112
00:13:57,200 --> 00:13:59,953
I just sent him.
It'll take two or three days.

113
00:14:00,120 --> 00:14:03,112
- Let's go and watch.
- OK. Let's go.

114
00:14:22,480 --> 00:14:24,436
He's fast.

115
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:31,077
Mr Novak, I'm so excited. I've never
seen a movie star up close before.

116
00:14:31,240 --> 00:14:32,559
Enjoy yourself.

117
00:14:32,720 --> 00:14:34,233
It's Jerry Lewis.

118
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:37,710
Mother used to take me to see him
when I was a kid.

119
00:14:37,880 --> 00:14:39,916
He'll be here in a moment.

120
00:14:40,080 --> 00:14:43,550
Be sure that all the accommodations
are exactly as he ordered.

121
00:14:43,720 --> 00:14:46,109
Whatever you do, be pleasant.

122
00:14:46,280 --> 00:14:49,352
There he is. Places, everybody. Places.

123
00:16:01,560 --> 00:16:05,314
- No autographs, please.
- Stand back, folks.

124
00:16:05,480 --> 00:16:07,516
Stand back. No autographs.

125
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:18,474
Hold it. Hold it. Hold it.

126
00:16:22,960 --> 00:16:26,555
- Is this where we register?
- Yes, sir. Right this way.

127
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:31,395
Hold it. Hold it!

128
00:16:31,560 --> 00:16:33,790
Hold it. Back. Hold it.

129
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:36,110
Hold it. Hold it!

130
00:16:37,080 --> 00:16:39,071
Stop with the brushing.

131
00:16:39,240 --> 00:16:41,196
We've been together a long time.

132
00:16:41,360 --> 00:16:44,272
I've asked you many things
and you've come through for me.

133
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:48,991
Now I'm asking you to hold it.
Stop pushing, stop rushing, just hold it.

134
00:16:49,160 --> 00:16:53,278
We're all adults and I'll expect you all
to conduct yourselves as an adult will.

135
00:16:53,440 --> 00:16:57,718
Hold it. I've never asked you this
but I'm asking you now, simply, purely,

136
00:16:57,880 --> 00:16:59,632
hold it!

137
00:16:59,800 --> 00:17:03,110
I'm a nervous wreck.
Let me have a cigarette.

138
00:17:04,440 --> 00:17:06,670
- Thank you. A light?
- Yes, sir.

139
00:17:06,840 --> 00:17:09,149
All right. All right. All right!

140
00:17:11,360 --> 00:17:12,759
Hold it.

141
00:17:12,920 --> 00:17:16,037
Stop with the brushing.
Another cigarette, please.

142
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:18,156
I'll smoke it dry.

143
00:17:18,320 --> 00:17:21,995
Mr Lewis, we're all excited about
your appearance at the Fontainebleau.

144
00:17:22,160 --> 00:17:27,188
We should be used to celebrities by now.
We've had some of the big ones staying.

145
00:17:27,360 --> 00:17:29,715
Wrong Way Corrigan.

146
00:17:29,880 --> 00:17:31,359
Ma Perkins.

147
00:17:31,520 --> 00:17:34,034
And don't forget Bill Holden's aunt.

148
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:36,270
Bill Holden's aunt. Yes.

149
00:17:39,160 --> 00:17:44,393
I would like very much, if you don't mind,
to get to my room as soon as possible.

150
00:17:44,560 --> 00:17:47,472
- Did you have a pleasant journey?
- Fine.

151
00:17:48,120 --> 00:17:49,678
He's so funny.

152
00:17:49,840 --> 00:17:52,832
This is the private entrance to the hotel.

153
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:56,913
Your suite is on the fifth floor and
totally secluded. I'm sure you'll like it.

154
00:17:57,080 --> 00:17:58,559
That's wonderful.

155
00:17:58,720 --> 00:18:01,792
- He's always good for a laugh.
- He sure is funny.

156
00:18:01,960 --> 00:18:04,110
I would like the seclusion and privacy.

157
00:18:04,280 --> 00:18:08,956
I had a terrible mishap a week ago
in the family. An aunt died and...

158
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:13,196
Nothing like a laugh!

159
00:18:14,600 --> 00:18:16,272
He sure is funny!

160
00:18:18,160 --> 00:18:22,631
- Would you care to register, Mr Lewis?
- I'd like to register and go to the room.

161
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:24,233
All right!

162
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:25,913
I need another card.

163
00:18:26,080 --> 00:18:29,311
It's all right. You may register
in your suite. This way.

164
00:18:29,480 --> 00:18:31,357
Thank you very much. I...

165
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:33,476
Back, back!

166
00:18:33,640 --> 00:18:34,959
Back!

167
00:18:35,120 --> 00:18:38,908
We're gonna go in the elevator and we're
gonna go single file like nice people.

168
00:18:39,080 --> 00:18:41,833
- Remember, hold it. Leon?
- Yes, chief?

169
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,673
- Who are all these people?
- They all work for you.

170
00:18:44,840 --> 00:18:46,910
Who's the guy with the straw hat?

171
00:18:47,080 --> 00:18:48,991
He's the guy that tells you who we are.

172
00:18:49,160 --> 00:18:53,392
That's good. I wouldn't have known.
I got such a bunch of people.

173
00:18:53,560 --> 00:18:56,757
This is a very nice room.
Where's the bed? Oh, it's the elevator.

174
00:18:56,920 --> 00:18:58,797
Wait, don't push.

175
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:00,678
That's it. Just file in.

176
00:19:00,840 --> 00:19:05,311
Move to your left. That's it. Now let me
get in. Let me get into the side.

177
00:19:05,480 --> 00:19:08,756
That's it. Get off.
You're stepping on my suede...

178
00:19:08,920 --> 00:19:10,638
Will you stop with the brushing?

179
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:15,316
I'm awfully sorry, Ben. These people
are just so overanxious.

180
00:19:15,480 --> 00:19:17,948
I appreciate it.
You've got to have your staff.

181
00:19:18,120 --> 00:19:21,157
I've got a barber and a gardener
and people assisting me.

182
00:19:21,320 --> 00:19:25,518
When I do the shows I try my best
to do what I can to perform

183
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:29,389
and I need the elements and
all of these people function for me...

184
00:19:29,560 --> 00:19:31,710
Stop brushing.

185
00:19:36,400 --> 00:19:39,392
- Are you thinking what I'm thinking?
- Yeah.

186
00:19:39,560 --> 00:19:42,677
But there couldn't be two of them. Right?

187
00:19:43,840 --> 00:19:47,628
Right. Hey, Stanley couldn't be
a Clark Kent, could he?

188
00:19:47,800 --> 00:19:50,234
Don't be silly.

189
00:19:51,920 --> 00:19:54,718
But he could be a Lamont Cranston.

190
00:20:08,160 --> 00:20:09,798
Bell captain.

191
00:20:09,960 --> 00:20:13,396
He didn't? I'm sorry, sir.
Yes, sir, right away.

192
00:20:13,560 --> 00:20:15,039
Front boy.

193
00:20:15,200 --> 00:20:19,955
That brown rawhide bag goes up
to the Lewis entourage. On the double.

194
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:46,030
Stanley. On the double!

195
00:20:58,280 --> 00:21:00,475
- There you are.
- For me, Mr Berle.

196
00:21:00,640 --> 00:21:03,677
Yes, ma'am. There are a lot
of autograph hounds.

197
00:21:03,840 --> 00:21:06,479
Mr Berle, my little daughter sings.

198
00:21:06,640 --> 00:21:09,677
She sings every time the neighbours
come over. What should I do?

199
00:21:09,840 --> 00:21:11,193
Move.

200
00:21:12,680 --> 00:21:15,558
Deliver this to Milton Berle right away.

201
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:23,718
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

202
00:21:23,880 --> 00:21:26,235
- Please?
- Sure, young lady.

203
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:31,838
You know, you look like a girl I know
from New York.

204
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,036
Were you ever...? Just a minute, son.

205
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:36,350
Are you down here with your mother?

206
00:21:36,520 --> 00:21:40,672
Your mother's down here with you?
Just a minute, son, please.

207
00:21:40,840 --> 00:21:42,796
There you are, young lady.

208
00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:46,311
Would you do me a favour?

209
00:21:46,480 --> 00:21:50,473
You must learn never to interrupt
anybody when they're busy.

210
00:21:50,640 --> 00:21:54,918
I don't care what you want to say, but
you must learn etiquette, politeness.

211
00:21:55,080 --> 00:21:57,719
Don't look over there. Look at me.

212
00:21:57,880 --> 00:22:00,110
Be a good boy. Never interrupt people.

213
00:22:00,280 --> 00:22:04,512
The rudest thing to do is to interrupt
people when they're trying to...

214
00:22:04,680 --> 00:22:06,671
Oh, you have a message for me.

215
00:22:06,840 --> 00:22:09,434
I'm sorry. I didn't know. Here's a tip.

216
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:24,393
Milton.

217
00:22:25,600 --> 00:22:27,158
Hi, Milt.

218
00:22:28,600 --> 00:22:30,591
What's the matter?

219
00:22:31,640 --> 00:22:33,949
- Milty?
- You wouldn't believe it.

220
00:22:34,120 --> 00:22:36,588
You wouldn't believe it.

221
00:22:36,760 --> 00:22:38,751
Milton, what's the matter?

222
00:22:40,440 --> 00:22:43,352
- Message for Jerry Lewis.
- Right here, boy.

223
00:22:48,720 --> 00:22:50,950
- Mr Lewis.
- Yes?

224
00:22:51,920 --> 00:22:53,239
Thank you.

225
00:22:58,720 --> 00:23:00,517
What's the trouble, sir?

226
00:23:00,680 --> 00:23:03,672
Nothing. You wouldn't understand
or believe it.

227
00:23:14,520 --> 00:23:17,080
There's a lot of kooks in this hotel.

228
00:23:17,240 --> 00:23:19,071
Straighten up there!

229
00:23:51,920 --> 00:23:53,433
Let's go.

230
00:23:53,600 --> 00:23:55,556
- Where's Stanley?
- I don't know.

231
00:23:55,720 --> 00:23:59,190
- We said we'd wait for him.
- We'll miss the first race.

232
00:23:59,360 --> 00:24:03,399
Stanley, the races go on in 20 minutes.
You're off duty now.

233
00:24:03,560 --> 00:24:06,438
- We'll talk later. Let's go.
- Go get dressed.

234
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:09,353
Let's go. We'll meet you outside.

235
00:24:17,560 --> 00:24:19,994
- Where's Stanley now?
- Who knows?

236
00:24:20,160 --> 00:24:22,720
- Let's go.
- We're late already.

237
00:24:25,880 --> 00:24:28,440
He's a speedy boy!

238
00:24:36,120 --> 00:24:38,031
What do you think, Herkie?

239
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:40,839
I can't make up my mind.
How about you, Dave?

240
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:44,310
I'm thinking.
Sonny, how does it look to you?

241
00:24:44,480 --> 00:24:47,278
Well, I don't know.

242
00:24:47,440 --> 00:24:51,194
Looks like our friend Flicka
has vanished again.

243
00:24:51,360 --> 00:24:55,433
- Where did this kid go?
- He probably went to make a bet.

244
00:24:55,600 --> 00:24:58,990
I don't have to go nowhere
to bet he's into mischief.

245
00:24:59,160 --> 00:25:02,277
<i>Attention, please.
May we have your attention?</i>

246
00:25:02,440 --> 00:25:07,150
<i>Due to circumstances beyond our
control we have to cancel the first race.</i>

247
00:25:07,320 --> 00:25:10,596
<i>We are very sorry. Please make
